  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">TLDA-Empowering young men and women to advocate for peace and challenge hate speech in Myanmar.</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">1. Religious coexistence and harmony strengthened through female and male youth (aged 18&#x2013;25) from religious and secular educational institutions. 
2. Ethnic and religious hate speech is challenged, creating an environment more conducive to social cohesion, by female and male youth</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The project aims to empower young men and women to become change-agents for peace in Myanmar with a particular focus on Mon and Rakhine states and Mandalay region. 400 youth trainee religious leaders (40% female) in Mandalay and Mon, 600 Buddhist and Muslim youth in Rakhine (50% female) undergo a program of peace education that is integrated into the targeted religious and educational institutions. PE curriculum will be developed and deliver the peace education program in Rakhine. Deliver anti-hate speech and media literacy training. Peace Innovation Lab micro-grants will be open for peace education trainees in the institutions, encouraging them to take further action.</narrative>
  </description>
